Data Science Programming

Practicum 1: Understanding Basic Data Types and Data Structures in R

21-22.9.2021

Devil’s first touch

One of the most basic ways to use R is as a calculator. We enter many math functions directly into the R Console.

Arithmetic operators

R can handle most simple types of math operators.Note that the expressions are evaluated from left to right. Exponentiation has the highest priority, followed by division, multiplication, substraction and addition. Priority can be adjusted by using round brackets.

  • + Addition, e.g. x + y
  • - Subtraction
  • * Multiplication
  • / Division
  • ^ or ** Exponentiation
1+2
## [1] 3
2*5
## [1] 10
2*(5+1)
## [1] 12

We can also use many other math functions. All of these are included in base R without any extra packages.

3^(1/2) # Exponential
## [1] 1.732051
log10(3.12311) # Log base 10
## [1] 0.4945873

Logical operators

Another important feature of R is the ability to use logic. This is not unique to R as all programming languages can do this, but it will be extremely useful when working with data.

Operator Description
< Less than
> Greater than
<= Less than or equal to
>= Greater than or equal to
== Exactly equal to
!= Not equal to
!a Not a
a & b a AND b
a | b a OR b

We can then see an example of this. Say, we use vector a containing integers 1 to 12. If we wanted to know where a>9 or where a<4, we would expect to see the values 1 2 3 10 11 12.

a <- 1:12
a > 9
##  [1] FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE

We can see that what R gives is are Boolean values as to whether or not each element of a is greater than 9. Similarly, we can get the same for a<4.

One simple thing we might try is to just combine these 2 values into a conditional by using OR.

a > 9 | a < 4
##  [1]  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE

This again just gives us Booleans and not necessarily the values that we were hoping to see. But, we use this to index a in the following manner:

a[a>9 | a<4]
## [1]  1  2  3 10 11 12

We will look at indexing with much further detail as we move through this course.

Further operators

There are other operators that we will use that are not necesssarily mathematical in nature. Each one of them is crucial for the use of R.

Description R symbol Example
Comment # # This is a comment
Assignment <- or = x <- 5 or x = 5
Concatenation operator c c(1,2,3)
Modular %% 25 %% 6
Sequence operator : 1 : 3
Boolean inclusion %in% 2 %in% 1:10
Pipe %>% 1>10 %>% +2 {Tidyverse}
Bi-directional pipe %<>% a %<>% +2 {Magrittr}

Package bundles

In R, the fundamental unit of shareable code is the package. A package bundles together code, data, documentation, and tests, and is easy to share with others. As of June 2019, there were over 14,000 packages available on the Comprehensive R Archive Network, or CRAN, the public clearing house for R packages. This huge variety of packages is one of the reasons that R is so successful: the chances are that someone has already solved a problem that you’re working on, and you can benefit from their work by downloading their package.

  • You install them from CRAN with install.packages("x").
  • You use them in R with library("x").
  • You get help on them with help(package = "x").

Atomic vectors

Vectors are the most important data structures in R. Unlike vectors in mathematics, we might think of a vector as something that has a magnitude and a direction, and that can be represented by a sequence of numbers. In its notion of a vector, R keeps the idea of a sequence but discards magnitude and direction.

For R, a vector is simply a sequence of elements. There are two general sort of vectors:

  • atomic vectors are usually product types and come in one of six forms called vector types;
  • recursive vectors are implemented as algebraic data types whose elements can be any sort of R-object at all.
Homogeneous Heterogeneous
1D Atomic vector Recursive vector (List)
2D Matrix Data frame
Multi Array

For now we will just study atomic vectors. Four primary types of atomic vectors are recognized: logical, integer, double, and character (which contains strings). Collectively integer and double vectors are known as numeric vectors.

  • character: "a" , "swc"
  • numeric: 2 , 15.5
  • integer: 2L (the L tells R to store this as an integer)
  • logical: TRUE , FALSE
  • complex: 1+4i (complex numbers with real and imaginary parts)

Numeric vectors

The general pattern for vector initialization is vector(class of object, length). We can also create vectors by concatenating a pre-defined set of elements using the c() function, or as a sequence of numbers. For example, let’s create a numeric vector object that will be accessible by name x. Note that the association <- equates to = that is commonly used in other programming languages. R also uses <<- to which we will come later.

integer(2) # Creates an empty vector of length 2.
## [1] 0 0
x <- 1:3 # Creates a vector as a sequence of numbers.
x <- c(1, 2, 3) # Creates a numeric vector with elements 1, 2 and 3 a associates it with name`x.
x # Note R prints the content of an object after providing its name on the screen. 
## [1] 1 2 3

Vectorized operations

Vectors are one part of a story, but the real power comes from R fully supporting vectorized operations. This is a deep piece of engineering in the design, but most of R will think quite happily in terms of vectors. For example, if we wanted to double all the values in the vector, we type the following.

2 * x # multiplies each element of a list by 2
## [1] 2 4 6

We can also add scalars, get the maximum and minimum values and so on. Note that ; separates multiple commands in the same line. 

x + 0.01
## [1] 1.01 2.01 3.01
min(x) ; mean(x) ; max(x)
## [1] 1
## [1] 2
## [1] 3

Logical and Character Vectors

x is a numeric vector, which constitutes the most common kind. They are numeric objects and are treated as double precision real numbers. To explicitly create integers, add a L at the end.

In a similar vein, we can create logical vectors y <- c(TRUE, TRUE, FALSE, FALSE) and character vectors z <- c("Alec", "Dan", "Rob", "Rich") using the same left association.

These objects with numeric vectors represent most vector types in R, implying the following hierarchy.

Every vector has common properties, which can be examined with tools provided by R. For example, we can ask:

  • class() - what kind of object is it (high level) ?
  • typeof() - what is the object’s data type (low level) ?
  • length() - how long is it ?
  • attributes() - does it have any attached metadata ?
class(x) ; typeof(x) ; length(x)
## [1] "numeric"
## [1] "double"
## [1] 3

Factors

A factor is a special type of vector that can contain only predefined values. It is used to store categorical data. Factors are built on top of an integer vector with two attributes: a class, “factor”, which makes it behave differently from regular integer vectors, and levels, which defines the set of allowed values.

z <- factor(c("a", "b", "b", "a"))
z
## [1] a b b a
## Levels: a b
levels(z)
## [1] "a" "b"

Factors are useful when we know the set of possible values but they’re not all present in a given dataset. In contrast to a character vector, when a factor is tabulated (table()) we will get counts of all categories, even unobserved ones.

Ordered factors are a minor variation of factors. In general, they behave like regular factors, but the order of the levels is meaningful (low, medium, high) (a property that is automatically leveraged by some modelling and visualisation functions).

ordered(c("b", "b", "a", "c"), levels = c("c", "b", "a")) # ordered is a subclass of factor
## [1] b b a c
## Levels: c < b < a

Note: In base R we tend to encounter factors very frequently because many base R functions (like read.csv() and data.frame()) automatically convert character vectors to factors. This is suboptimal because there’s no way for those functions to know the set of all possible levels or their correct order: the levels are a property of theory or experimental design, not of the data. Instead, use the argument stringsAsFactors = FALSE to suppress this behaviour, and then manually convert character vectors to factors using your knowledge of the “theoretical” data.

Defining valuable subsets in R

R’s subsetting operators are fast and powerful, but subsetting in R is hard to master because you need to internalize a number of interrelated concepts:

  • There are six ways to subset atomic vectors.
  • There are three subsetting operators [[, [, and $.
  • Subsetting operations interact differently with different vector types (e.g atomic vectors, lists, factors, matrices and data frames.)
  • Subsetting can be combined with assignment.

Subsetting in a natural complement to str(). While str() shows you all the pieces of any objects and its structure, subsetting allows you to pull out the pieces you are interested in. For large complex objects, we highly recommend using the interactive RStudio Viewer, which you can activate View(mu_object).

Adding and removing elements

A vector in R can have infinite number of elements but we might want to remove some of them, or add the new ones. Adding one or more new elements to the vector can be done either by using c() for combine, or by using some of the existing wrappers, e.g. append().

c(x, 10) # Appends 10 to vector x.
## [1]  1  2  3 10
append(10, x)
## [1] 10  1  2  3

Removing elements from existing vectors is a wee bit more tricky. Sub-setting is usually carried out using square brackets [] following the vector’s name, in which we can:

  • use indices to denote which elements of a vector remain,
  • use Boolean operators to denote kept elements, or
  • use wrapper functions such as subset().

Now, let’s select elements of a vector x with values less than 2, or equal to 3. For inverse subsetting use -c().

x[c(1,3)]
## [1] 1 3
x[x < 2 | x == 3] # Subsetting vector using predicate.
## [1] 1 3
subset(x, x < 2 | x == 3) # Bespoke predicate function.
## [1] 1 3
LessThanTwo <- x < 2 ; x[LessThanTwo | x == 3]
## [1] 1 3
x[c(TRUE,FALSE,TRUE)] # Subsetting using logical vector.
## [1] 1 3
x[-2] # Subsetting by inverse selection.
## [1] 1 3

Modifying vector elements

To change vector value(s) simply combine subsetting with association, or use predicate function replace().

x <- 1:10
x[2] <- 20
x
##  [1]  1 20  3  4  5  6  7  8  9 10
x <- c(3,2,1,0,4,0)
x
## [1] 3 2 1 0 4 0
replace(x, x==0, 1)
## [1] 3 2 1 1 4 1

Missing variables

R represents missing, or unknown values, with special sentinel value: NA (short for not applicable). Missing values tend to be infectious: most computations involving a missing value will return another missing value. Let’s explore this behavious on the following atomic vector x

a <- 1:10 # Create a vector containing sequence of numbers from 1 to 10.
a[4] <- NA # Introduce NA to position 4. 
mean(a) # Calculate mean of vector `a`
## [1] NA

To fix this, you should use is.na() to get only non-NA elements. is.na() returns logical vector with TRUE for each position that contains NA. Use with ! for inverse selection.

a <- 1:10 ; a[4] <- NA
mean(a[!is.na(a)]) # Calculates mean from non-NA elements of a vector a
## [1] 5.666667

Object attributes

Each object of a vector can have multiple attributes, such as names, length, class and other arbitrary metadata. However, note that vectors may only have one type. Should multiple types are provided to the constructor, coercing occurs to create a vector that is the least common denominator. The coercion will always move towards the type that’s easiest to coerce to. Let’s see what happens here:

xx <- c(1.7, "a")
names(xx) <- c("double?", "character?")
xx
##    double? character? 
##      "1.7"        "a"
typeof(xx)
## [1] "character"
names(xx) <- NULL # Removes names of elements of a vector.

This is called implicit coercion. The coercion rule goes logical > integer > numeric > complex > character. You can also coerce vectors explicitly using the as.<class_name>.

Binding basics

Consider this code: x <- c(1,2,3). It’s easy to read it as: “create an object named ‘x’, containing the values 1, 2, and 3”. Unfortunately, that’s a simplification that will lead to inaccurate predictions about what R is actually doing behind the scenes. It’s more accurate to say that this code is doing two things:

  • It’s creating an object, a vector of values c(1,2,3),
  • And it’s binding that object to name x.

The name, x, is drawn with a rounded rectangle. It has an arrow that points to (or binds or references) the value, the vector c(1, 2, 3). The arrow points in opposite direction to the assignment arrow: <- creates a binding from the name on the left-hand side to the object on the right-hand side.

Copy on Modify

Let’s bind x and y to the same underlying value and then modify y.

x <- c(1, 2, 3)
y <- x
y[[3]] <- 4
x ; y
## [1] 1 2 3
## [1] 1 2 4

Modifying y clearly didn’t modify x. So what happened to the shared binding? While the value associated with y changed, the original object did not. Instead, R created a new object with one value changed, then rebound y to that object.

This behavior is called copy-on-modify. Understanding it will radically improve your intuition about the performance of R code. A related way to describe this behavior is to say that R objects are unchangeable, or immutable.

You can see when an object gets copied with the help of base::tracemem(). Once you call that function with an object, you’ll get the object’s current address.

tracemem(x) ; tracemem(y) # Print memory IDs for objects x and y.
## [1] "<0000000017EEC0F8>"
## [1] "<0000000018A5BD18>"

Modify-in-place

As we’ve seen above, modifying an R object usually creates a copy. There are two exceptions:

  • Objects with a single binding get a special performance optimization.
  • Environments, a special type of object, are always modified in place.

Thus, when it comes to bindings, R can currently only count 0, 1, or many. That means that if an object has two bindings, and one goes away, the reference count does not go back to 1: one less than many is still many. In turn, this means that R will make copies when it sometimes doesn’t need to. Moreover, whenever you call the vast majority of functions, it makes a reference to the object. The only exception are specially written “primitive” C functions. These can only be written by R-core and occur mostly in the base package.

Casting vectors into arrays

Arrays are data storage objects in R containing more than or equal to 1 dimension. Arrays can contain only a single data type. The array() function is an in-built function which takes input as a vector and arranges them according to dim argument. Array is an iterable object, where the array elements are indexed, accessed and modified individually.

Uni-dimensional arrays are called vectors in R. Two-dimensional arrays are called matrices. To construct an array from a vector, simply add two or more dimension to an existing vector. As usual, there are multuple ways to do it.

x <- 1:8 # Creates a vector of 8 consecutive integers, starting with 1.
dim(x) <- c(2,2,2)
dimnames(x) <- list(c("Alpha", "Beta"), c("Gamma", "Delta"), c("Prima","Sekunda")) # Adds names to each dimension.

# Alternatively, we can use one of available constructors.
x <- 1:8 
# Syntax: array(array1, dim = c (r, c, m), dimnames = list(c.names, r.names, m.names))
array(x, dim = c(2,2,2), dimnames = list(c("Alpha", "Beta"), c("Gamma", "Delta"), c("Prima","Sekunda"))) 
## , , Prima
## 
##       Gamma Delta
## Alpha     1     3
## Beta      2     4
## 
## , , Sekunda
## 
##       Gamma Delta
## Alpha     5     7
## Beta      6     8

Matrices in R are a table-like structures consisting of elements arranged in a fixed number of rows and columns. All the elements belong to a single data type. R contains an in-built function matrix() to create a matrix. Elements of a matrix can be accessed by providing indexes of rows and columns. The arithmetic operation, addition, subtraction, and multiplication can be performed on matrices with the same dimensions.

To create a matrix, we follow the same procedure using a dedicated constructor.

# Syntax: matrix(data, nrow, ncol, byrow)
x <- 1:8 # Creates a vector of 8 consecutive integers, starting with 1.
matrix(x, nrow = 2, ncol = 4, byrow = TRUE) # Use available constructor to transform one-dimensional vector to a matrix.
##      [,1] [,2] [,3] [,4]
## [1,]    1    2    3    4
## [2,]    5    6    7    8

However, unlike arrays, matrices can be build from different vectors which are of a same type and length.

x <- 1:5
y <- 6:10
matrix(c(x,y), nrow = 5) # A matrix with five rows is build from two vectors.
##      [,1] [,2]
## [1,]    1    6
## [2,]    2    7
## [3,]    3    8
## [4,]    4    9
## [5,]    5   10
cbind(x, y) # Column-wise binding of vectors x and y.
##      x  y
## [1,] 1  6
## [2,] 2  7
## [3,] 3  8
## [4,] 4  9
## [5,] 5 10
rbind(x, y) # Row-wise binding of vectors x and y.
##   [,1] [,2] [,3] [,4] [,5]
## x    1    2    3    4    5
## y    6    7    8    9   10

Let’s summarize the basic differences between matrices and arrays below.

Arrays Matrices
Arrays can contain greater than or equal to 1 dimensions. Matrices contains 2 dimensions in a table like structure.
Array is a homogeneous data structure. Matrix is also a homogeneous data structure.
It is a singular vector arranged into the specified dimensions. It comprises of multiple equal length vectors stacked together in a table.
array() function can be used to create matrix by specifying the third dimension to be 1. matrix() function however can be used to create at most 2-dimensional array.
Arrays are superset of matrices. Matrices are a subset, special case of array where dimensions is two.
Limited set of collection-based operations. Wide range of collection operations possible.
Mostly, intended for storage of data. Mostly, matrices are intended for data transformation.

Attributes

The following table shows, how many of the functions for working with vectors have generalizations for matrices and arrays.

Operation Vector Matrix Array
Get names names() rownames();colnames() dimnames()
Get length length() nrow();ncol() dim()
Append c() rbind();cbind() abind()
Transpose - t() aperm()

Subsetting arrays

Subsetting matrices and arrays follows the same principles as subsetting of vectors. We can do it either by using element indexes or logical vectors. consider this code:

matrix1 <- matrix(1:10, nrow = 5) # Creates a matrix with 5 rows
rownames(matrix1) <- c("Alpha", "Beta", "Gamma", "Delta", "Epsilon") 
colnames(matrix1) <- c("Prima", "Sekunda")
matrix1
##         Prima Sekunda
## Alpha       1       6
## Beta        2       7
## Gamma       3       8
## Delta       4       9
## Epsilon     5      10
matrix1[c(TRUE,TRUE, FALSE, FALSE, FALSE), 1:2] # To subset a matrix, we must provide either a logical vector, or indexes of elements that should be kept.
##       Prima Sekunda
## Alpha     1       6
## Beta      2       7

In a similar vein, filtering operation use predicate statement that are supplied in square brackets. For example, let’s filter matrix1 such that only rows where the values of the second column higher than 8 are provided. This is carried out in two steps:

  • Create a logical vector, e.g. include all elements from the second column of a matrix that are greater than 8.
  • Use that vector for subsetting rows.
matrix1[, "Sekunda"] >8 # Select elements from "Sekunda" that are greater than 8. Return logical vector.
##   Alpha    Beta   Gamma   Delta Epsilon 
##   FALSE   FALSE   FALSE    TRUE    TRUE
selectMe <- matrix1[, "Sekunda"] >8 # 

matrix1[selectMe,] # Use that vector for subsetting rows.
##         Prima Sekunda
## Delta       4       9
## Epsilon     5      10

Excercises

1. Explain the relationship between objects a, b, c and d. Use tracemen() to check your answer.

a <- 1:10
b <- a
a[2] <- 4
c <- b
d <- 1:10

2. Write a R program to add two vectors of integers with length 3.

3. Use the following code to create vector x.

x <- 1:10 ; x[c(1,4,8)] <- NA
x
##  [1] NA  2  3 NA  5  6  7 NA  9 10

For a given vector x, is.na(x) returns logical vector with TRUE for each position that contains NA. Use is.na() together with knowledge you gathered about atomic vector subsetting to convert all NAs in x to 4.

4. Consider the following code.

x <- 1:10 ; matrix(x, 2,5)
##      [,1] [,2] [,3] [,4] [,5]
## [1,]    1    3    5    7    9
## [2,]    2    4    6    8   10

At which row and column of a matrix will the number 8 occur?

5. Let’s use pseudo-random number generator to create to vectors x and y.

set.seed(123) # Sets an initial value for pseudo random generator of numbers. 
x <- rnorm(20, mean = 10, sd = 5) # Generates 20 random values that have mean of 10 and standard deviation of 5. 
y <- rnorm(20, mean = 5, sd = 15) # Generates another 20 random values that have mean of 5 and standard deviation of 15.

How many rows in a column-bound matrix xy contain values that are higher than 5 in x and less than 2 in y?

6. Motor Trend Car Road Test is a preloaded dataset in R that contains fuel consumption and 10 aspects of design and performance for 32 automobiles published by 1974 Motor Trend US magazine. You can assess it just by typing mtcars. This data frame has 32 observations on 11 numeric variables.

col. col.name coll.name in full

[, 4] hp Gross horsepower
[, 5] drat Rear axle ratio
[, 6] wt Weight (1000 lbs)
[, 7] qsec 1/4 mile time
[, 8] vs Engine (0 = V-shaped, 1 = straight)

Use subsetting operations to:

  • find all car models with motor that has 6 cylinders.
  • find the car model with the highest horsepower, but limited to transmission with only three gears.
  • find how many cars have cylinder displacement between 100 and 120 cubic inches and have 2 carburetors.
